Grading Rubric: Argumentative Essay
Category	Distinguished	Proficient	Basic	Below Expectations	Non-Performance
Introduction

15 Points

Introduction paragraph exceeds 3 sentences, begins with an engaging hook capturing reader interest, introduces the topic effectively, and includes a thesis statement that provides a clear position on the argument with smooth connection to the first body paragraph.

12 Points

Introduction paragraph exceeds 3 sentences, starts with a clear hook introducing the topic, and contains a thesis statement explicitly stating the position on the argument.

9 Points

Introduction paragraph has at least 3 sentences, includes a weak or unengaging hook, and provides a thesis statement mentioning the position on the argument without clear detail or clarity.

6 Points

Introduction paragraph has at least 3 sentences but lacks a hook or provides a thesis statement about the position on the argument without adequate clarity or detail.

3 Points

Introduction paragraph has fewer than 3 sentences, lacks a hook, does not include a clear thesis statement, and fails to adequately explain the position on the argument.

Body

15 Points

Body of the argumentative essay contains three paragraphs or more, each exceeding 3 sentences with one claim per paragraph. Each paragraph is fully developed, provides detailed examples to support the thesis, and contains effective transitions.

12 Points

Body of the argumentative essay body includes two paragraphs, each exceeding 3 sentences with one claim per paragraph, providing detailed examples to support the thesis.

9 Points

Body of the argumentative essay includes one paragraph of at least 3 sentences with at least one claim, giving general examples to support the thesis but lacks detailed specifics.

6 Points

Body of the argumentative essay contains one paragraph of at least 3 sentences with a claim but relevance to the thesis is unclear, making it challenging to understand.

3 Points

Body of argumentative essay is fewer than 3 sentences and does not adequately detail the claim or provide examples that support the thesis.

Organization

15 Points

Argumentative essay structure is highly organized with clearly identifiable beginning, middle, and end sections. Ideas flow logically, with strong, explicit transitions smoothly connecting each segment.

12 Points

Argumentative essay structure demonstrates clear organization, appropriate transitions between sections, and mostly logical sequencing of ideas and events.

9 Points

Argumentative essay exhibits basic structure, but transitions are inconsistent, occasionally causing confusion or disrupting logical sequence of ideas.

6 Points

Argumentative essay structure is disorganized, with weak or missing transitions, making ideas difficult to follow. Paragraphs jump between unrelated ideas or events, and sections may end abruptly.

3 Points

Argumentative essay lacks clear organizational structure; transitions are absent or inadequate, and ideas are scattered without cohesion or logical unity.

In-Text Citations

15 Points

Every claim is supported by a properly formatted MLA citation.

12 Points

Each body paragraph includes at least one MLA-formatted citation that supports the argument.

9 Points

At least two citations are present and support the argument, with only one formatted correctly in MLA style.

6 Points

At least two citations are present, but they either do not support the argument or are not correctly formatted in MLA style.

3 Points

Only one citation is present, but it either does not support the argument or is not correctly formatted in MLA style.

Conclusion

15 Points

Conclusion paragraph exceeds 3 sentences, provides a thoughtful and reflective summary that reinforces the thesis, and brings together all the points addressed in the essay. New details are not added.

12 Points

Conclusion paragraph exceeds 3 sentences, provides reflection that reinforces the thesis, and no new details are added.

9 Points

Conclusion paragraph has at least 3 sentences but contains only general reflection that reinforces the thesis but does not bring back all the points addressed in the essay. New details are not added.

6 Points

Conclusion paragraph has at least 3 sentences but lacks clear reflection that reinforces the thesis or brings back all the points addressed in the essay or includes new details.

3 Points

Conclusion paragraph is fewer than 3 sentences lacking enough detail to provide adequate closure.

Works Cited

15 Points

Works Cited page follows formatting and MLA citation guidelines.

12 Points

Works Cited page has two or three errors in formatting but follows MLA citation guidelines.

9 Points

Works Cited page has four to five errors in MLA formatting and citation guidelines.

6 Points

Works Cited page has more than five errors in MLA formatting and citation guidelines.

0 Points

Works Cited page was not submitted.

Mechanics

10 Points

Argumentative essay contains no errors in spelling, punctuation, or grammar, and demonstrates varied sentence structures.

8 Points

Argumentative essay contains few minor errors in spelling, punctuation, or grammar, and includes some sentence variety.

6 Points

Argumentative essay includes noticeable errors that slightly impact readability and exhibits limited sentence variety or repetitive structures.

4 Points

Argumentative essay contains frequent errors significantly impacting readability. Sentence structures are repetitive, unclear, or contain run-on sentences and fragments, though basic meaning remains understandable.

2 Points

Argumentative essay is severely compromised by numerous critical errors in spelling, punctuation, grammar, and sentence structure, making comprehension difficult or nearly impossible.

